[Comparing today's numbers with yesterday's (23 Jul 2020), the global case count rose by 1.8% in the past 24 hours. The USA and Brazil are still the most severely affected countries in terms of cumulative case counts, although India has been rapidly increasing, with daily case counts around 50 000. At this rate of daily new confirmations, the global tally will pass the 16 million mark by tomorrow [25 Jul 2020].

In the past 24 hours, the USA reported a record high of 78 336 cases, followed by Brazil (58 249) and India (48 892). These 3 countries account for almost half of all confirmed cases globally (49.8%). There were 6237 deaths reported in the past 24 hours.

In descending rank order, the USA is number one for the number of newly confirmed cases in the past 24 hours, followed by Brazil, India, South Africa, Mexico, Colombia, Russia, Argentina, Peru, and Bangladesh -- global hotspots. The range in the top 10 daily newly confirmed cases goes from 2548 to 78 336. Other hotspots are seen in the countries numbered 11-20 in this list: Chile, Iran, Iraq, Saudi Arabia, Spain, Philippines, Indonesia, Kazakhstan, Israel and the Dominican Republic -- their range of reported new cases is 1462 to 2545.

Comparing the 7-day averages of daily confirmed cases from the past 7 days and those from 8-14 days ago, there is an increase of 11.9%, and looking at daily reported deaths, the change is increased by 18.4%.

Impression: The SARS-CoV-2 is still actively being transmitted in all regions of the world, and many countries are showing increases in their daily newly confirmed case counts and mortality. That being said, the most severely affected region is the Americas with cases increasing on a daily basis, even though the comparative 7-day average suggests things may be slowing down (or reporting is slowing down). - Mod.MPP]
